Eyelid edema, also known as eyelid swelling or puffiness, is a common condition that occurs when there is excess fluid trapped in the tissues of the eyelid. It can be caused by a variety of factors such as allergies, infections, injury, or inflammation. Eyelid edema can cause discomfort and affect vision, making it important to seek treatment if you experience this symptom. If the swelling is mild, home remedies such as applying warm compresses or using cool cucumbers may help reduce the puffiness. However, if the swelling is severe or persistent, it's best to consult an eye doctor for further evaluation and treatment options.

Vagus nerve disease, also known as vagal nerve disorder or pneumogastric nerve disorder, is a condition that affects the Vagus nerve, which is the tenth cranial nerve. The Vagus nerve runs from the brain down to the neck and plays a role in various functions such as digestion, heart rate regulation, and vocalization.

Vagus nerve disease can cause symptoms such as difficulty swallowing (dysphagia), hoarseness or weak voice (dysphonia), and issues with speech (dysarthria). It can also affect the muscles of the face and neck, leading to weakness or paralysis. In some cases, it can cause problems with breathing.

Treatment for Vagus nerve disease depends on the underlying cause and may include medication, surgery, or a combination of both. It is important to consult a medical professional if you are experiencing any symptoms of Vagus nerve disease.

Vagina leiomyoma is a type of vaginal benign neoplasm, which refers to a non-cancerous growth or tumor in the vagina. It is characterized by the presence of smooth muscle cells and is typically benign, although it can cause discomfort, pain, or bleeding if left untreated. Vagina leiomyoma has a specific definition as a vaginal benign neoplasm that is a benign tumor of smooth muscle cells, with an exact synonym being leiomyoma of the vagina.

Bell's palsy is a condition where the facial muscles become weak or paralyzed on one side of the face. It occurs when the nerve that controls these muscles is damaged or compressed, resulting in temporary or permanent paralysis. Bell's palsy affects approximately 40,000 people per year in the United States and can occur at any age. Treatment typically involves medications to reduce inflammation and improve nerve function, as well as physical therapy to help restore strength and mobility to the affected muscles. In some cases, surgery may be necessary if the nerve is severely damaged or there is a risk of long-term complications such as muscle atrophy or scarring.
tuberculous epididymitis is a type of urogenital tuberculosis that affects the epididymis. It commonly causes symptoms such as pain and scrotal swelling.

Retinal ischemia, also known as retinal vascular disease or RVD, is a condition where the blood flow to the retina is restricted, leading to insufficient oxygen supply to the eye. This can cause damage to the retina and may even lead to blindness if left untreated. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience symptoms such as sudden vision loss, floaters, or pain in the eye.

Retinal perforation is a type of retinal detachment where a hole or tear forms in the retina. It is also sometimes referred to as retinal break, retinal dialysis, or retinal tear. Retinal detachment occurs when the retina becomes detached from its underlying support structure in the eye. This can happen due to various factors such as trauma, infections, or degenerative diseases like age-related macular degeneration and diabetic retinopathy. Symptoms of retinal perforation may include sudden vision loss, flashes of light, floaters, and a dark shadow in the field of vision. If left untreated, it can lead to permanent blindness. Therefore, it is crucial to seek medical attention if you experience any symptoms of retinal perforation. Treatment options may include surgery or laser therapy to repair the damage and prevent further complications.

Trichuriasis is a type of intestinal disease caused by the parasitic helminth Trichuris trichiura. It is transmitted through ingestion of food contaminated with egg-carrying soil, and can lead to symptoms such as abdominal pain, diarrhea, rectal prolapse, and growth retardation in humans. It has a location in the intestine and can have a material basis in Trichuris trichiura. The disease is also known by other names such as Infection by Trichuris trichura, Trichuriasis infection, Whipworm disease, or trichuris trchiura infection.

bagassosis is a type of extrinsic allergic alveolitis, which is an industrial disease characterized by cough, difficult breathing, chills, fever, and prolonged weakness caused by the inhalation of the dust of bagasse containing thermophilic actinomycetes. It has the exact synonym sugar cane worker pneumonitis.

A plantar nerve lesion refers to a condition where there is damage or injury to the plantar nerve, which is one of the peripheral nerves in the lower limb. This type of mononeuritis affects the sole of the foot and can cause various symptoms such as pain, numbness, tingling, and weakness in the affected area. A lesion of the plantar nerve is a specific term used to describe this type of injury.

A lesion of the sciatic nerve, also known as mononeuritis of the lower limb, is a condition that affects only one of the two main branches of the sciatic nerve. The sciatic nerve runs from the lower back down through the legs, and a lesion can cause pain or numbness in the affected leg, foot, and ankle. It's possible for this condition to be caused by a variety of factors, including trauma, infection, or inflammation. The location of the lesion can vary depending on which part of the sciatic nerve is affected, but it typically involves one or more branches that innervate the muscles and skin of the lower limb. Treatment for a lesion of the sciatic nerve may involve physical therapy, medication, or surgery, depending on the underlying cause and severity of the condition.

Tibial nerve palsy is a condition where the tibial nerve, which runs down the front of the leg, is weakened or paralyzed. This can cause problems with muscle function and movement in the lower leg and foot. It's not clear what you are asking about the intersection of disease and location of the tibial nerve, but it sounds like you may be asking if the condition known as "tibial nerve palsy" is related to a specific location of the tibial nerve. The answer is yes, tibial nerve palsy is specifically related to the weakening or paralysis of the tibial nerve.

von Willebrand's disease is a type of blood coagulation disorder that is characterized by an abnormality in the von Willebrand factor (vWF) protein. This protein is necessary for proper platelet function and blood clot formation. Individuals with von Willebrand's disease may experience excessive bleeding, particularly after minor injuries or surgeries. It is important to note that this condition can be inherited and is often diagnosed in childhood. Treatment options for von Willebrand's disease typically involve managing blood clotting factors and preventing or treating bleeding episodes as they occur.

That is correct. Hypermobility of the coccyx, also known as coccygeal hypermobility syndrome, is a condition characterized by excessive movement or instability of the tailbone (coccyx). It can cause pain, discomfort, and other symptoms. Proper diagnosis and treatment are essential to manage this condition effectively. If you suspect that you have coccygeal hypermobility syndrome, it is important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and care.

I understand that you are trying to provide information about a medical condition called trichostrongylosis, which is characterized by infection with the parasite Trichostrongylus colubriformis or Trichostrongylus axei. This infection can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, diarrhea, anorexia, headache, fatigue, anemia, and eosinophilia. Hepatitis A is a viral infectious disease that affects the liver. It is caused by the Hepatitis A virus, which can be transmitted through contaminated food or water, or by direct contact with an infected person. The symptoms of Hepatitis A include fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, clay-colored bowel movements, joint pain, and jaundice. It is also known as viral hepatitis A.

Hepatic coma, also known as hepatic encephalopathy, is a serious condition that occurs when the liver is not functioning properly. This can lead to a buildup of toxins in the bloodstream, which can cause damage to the brain and other organs. Symptoms of hepatic coma may include confusion, lethargy, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and decreased urine output. In severe cases, it can lead to a coma or even death. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or someone you know may be experiencing hepatic coma.

hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS) is a rare but serious condition that affects multiple organ systems, including the kidneys, brain, and gastrointestinal tract. It is caused by an autoimmune attack on red blood cells, which leads to the formation of microclot

Duane retraction syndrome is a type of strabismus that occurs when the eye's internal muscles become too weak or overly tight, causing the eyeball to be pushed back into the skull. This can lead to double vision and other visual problems. It is also known as Duane's syndrome and Stilling-Turk-Duane syndrome.

Chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia (CPEO) is a type of mitochondrial myopathy that affects the muscles responsible for eye movements. It is characterized by gradual weakness and atrophy of the muscles around the eyes, leading to difficulty in movement, double vision, and potential blindness if left untreated.

In contrast, progressive external ophthalmoplegia specifically refers to a group of disorders that affect eye movements but do not necessarily involve muscle weakness or atrophy. It is important to differentiate between the two conditions as treatment options may vary. If you suspect you have CPEO or any other eye condition, it is advisable to consult with an ophthalmologist for proper diagnosis and management.

Idiopathic juvenile osteoporosis is a type of osteoporosis that has no known cause and typically affects children during their growth and development. It is characterized by pain in the back and extremities, walking difficulties, multiple fractures, and radiological evidence of osteoporosis. The exact synonym for this condition is Idiopathic osteoporosis, and it can also be referred to as juvenile osteoporosis.

That is correct. Ulceration of the vulva, also known as lichen sclerosus et atrophicus (LSEA), is a chronic inflammatory condition that causes thinning and hardening of the vulvar tissue. It can lead to the formation of painful ulcers on the skin of the vulva, which may cause itching or discomfort. Other symptoms may include vaginal dryness, dyspareunia (pain during sexual intercourse), and a burning sensation while urinating. LSEA can have a significant impact on a woman's quality of life, but with proper treatment, it is possible to manage the symptoms and improve her comfort.

Dyscalculia is a learning disability that affects an individual's ability to understand and process mathematical concepts, memorize math facts, organize numbers, and solve problems. It is also known as Mathematics Disorder or Disorder of Arithmetical Skills.

Phacolytic glaucoma is a type of phacogenic glaucoma. Phacogenic glaucoma refers to a group of eye diseases that are caused by the abnormal metabolism or accumulation of proteins in the lens, leading to increased risk of developing glaucoma. Phacolytic glaucoma specifically is characterized by acute onset of open-angle glaucoma secondary to a leaking mature or hypermature cataract and has symptoms such as chronic progressive vision loss, acute onset of pain, redness, and blurry vision. It's caused by direct obstruction of aqueous outflow pathways from leaking cataractous lens proteins.

Phacogenic glaucoma is a specific type of glaucoma characterized by optic atrophy resulting from a lens abnormality, leading to progressive decreased vision, especially in the peripheral area. It can be caused by cataracts, trauma to the eye, or age-related damage that obstructs aqueous outflow, leading to increased intraocular pressure and optic nerve atrophy with associated vision loss.

Posterior uveitis is indeed a type of panuveitis, and it involves inflammation in the posterior part (back) of the eye. The condition can cause pain, redness, and blurred vision. It is important to consult an ophthalmologist for proper diagnosis and treatment.

That is correct. Urethral obstruction refers to the blockage or narrowing of the urethra, which can cause difficulties in urination and other complications if left untreated. Common causes of urethral obstruction include benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), prostatitis, trauma, and certain types of cancer. Treatment options may depend on the underlying cause and severity of the obstruction, but can include medications, lifestyle changes, or surgery. It is important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Cri du chat syndrome is a genetic disorder characterized by developmental delays, intellectual disability, and distinctive physical features. It occurs due to a deletion of the short arm of chromosome 5 (5p16.3). The condition is known for its high-pitched cry that sounds like a cat's meow.

olecranon bursitis is a medical condition that affects the olecranon, which is the pointy end of the elbow. It is caused by inflammation of the bursa, a small sac filled with fluid that helps to cushion and lubricate the joint. This inflammation can cause pain, swelling, and stiffness in the affected area.
olecranon bursitis is often caused by repetitive overhead motion or prolonged pressure on the elbow. It can also be caused by a fall or a blow to the elbow. In some cases, it may be associated with other medical conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis or gout. Treatment for olecranon bursitis usually involves resting the affected area, applying ice to reduce swelling, and taking nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) to relieve pain and inflammation. In more severe cases, corticosteroid injections may be necessary. Physical therapy may also be recommended to help improve range of motion and strengthen the muscles around the elbow.

Velocardiofacial syndrome (VCFS), also known as Shprintzen syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by a hemizygous deletion of chromosome 22q11.2. This results in the loss of several genes, including TBX1, which plays an essential role in cardiac development. VCFS can cause a range of physical and mental health issues, often affecting multiple organ systems. Common symptoms include heart defects, facial abnormalities, low muscle tone, and developmental delays. Diagnosis is usually made through chromosome analysis or karyotyping, followed by genetic counseling to discuss the implications of the diagnosis for the individual and their family. Treatment may involve surgery, medication, and physical therapy to address specific symptoms and improve overall quality of life.

Potter syndrome, also known as Potter sequence, is a congenital disorder that affects newborn infants. It is characterized by underdevelopment of the kidneys and lungs due to a combination of factors such as oligohydramnios (low amniotic fluid volume), compression in the uterus, and renal agenesis (absence of one or both kidneys).

Potter syndrome can lead to serious health complications for newborn infants, including respiratory distress, poor feeding, low blood sugar levels, and high blood pressure. Early diagnosis and intervention are crucial in managing the symptoms and ensuring the best possible outcome for affected infants. Treatment may involve providing supplemental oxygen, managing fluid levels, and addressing any electrolyte imbalances that may arise. In some cases, dialysis or kidney transplantation may be necessary to support the affected infant's renal function.

It is important for healthcare providers to be aware of Potter syndrome as a potential complication during pregnancy and delivery, especially in cases where there are risk factors such as low amniotic fluid volume or a history of renal agenesis. Early detection and appropriate care can significantly improve outcomes for infants with this condition.

That is correct. Parametritis, also known as pelvic cellulitis, is a type of inflammation that affects the parametrium, which is the tissue that surrounds the uterus and other reproductive organs in the female pelvis. It can be caused by various factors such as bacterial infections, sexually transmitted diseases, or non-infectious causes like endometriosis or ectopic pregnancy. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, fever, and tenderness to touch. Treatment typically involves antibiotics and bed rest, depending on the underlying cause of the inflammation.

acute leukemia is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells in the body. It occurs when the bone marrow produces an excessive number of abnormal white blood cells, which then enter the bloodstream and can spread to other parts of the body. There are different types of acute leukemia, including lymphoid leukemia and myeloid leukemia. Lymphoid leukemia affects the lymphatic system, while myeloid leukemia affects the myeloid cells in the bone marrow. Acute leukemia is a serious condition that requires immediate medical attention and treatment.

Perineocele is a condition where the tissue that supports the uterus and other pelvic organs weakens, causing the bulging or protrusion of the perineal area. It can occur during childbirth or after menopause when estrogen levels decrease, leading to a loss of support for the pelvic organs. Symptoms may include discomfort, pain, and a feeling of heaviness in the lower abdomen or pelvic region. Treatment options depend on the severity of the condition and can range from conservative measures such as exercise and Kegel exercises to more invasive procedures like surgery. It is important to consult with a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Hypertrophic pyloric stenosis is a type of congenital anomaly, characterized by the thickening of the muscle around the pylorus in infants. This can lead to severe vomiting and difficulty with feeding. It is also sometimes referred to as congenital or infantile stricture of the pylorus. Treatment typically involves surgery to widen the pylorus and alleviate the symptoms.

Hiatus hernia occurs when the upper part of the stomach, known as the cardia, protrudes through a weak spot in the diaphragm. This can lead to symptoms such as heartburn and difficulty swallowing. In some cases, it may be congenital, meaning that it is present from birth. It can also occur later in life due to factors such as obesity or age-related weakening of the muscles. Treatment options include lifestyle changes, such as losing weight and eating smaller meals, as well as surgery in more severe cases.

Hiatus hernia is a medical condition where the upper part of the stomach and LES (lower esophageal sphincter) protrudes through the hiatus in the diaphragm. This can cause acid reflux and other digestive problems. It is also called hiatal hernia or diaphragmatic hiatus hernia.

Vestibulocochlear nerve disease, also known as acoustic neurinoma or cochleovestibular syndrome, is a type of retrocochlear disease that affects the vestibulocochlear nerve, which is responsible for hearing and balance. It is a cranial nerve disorder and can lead to symptoms such as hearing loss, tinnitus, dizziness or vertigo, and sometimes facial weakness. Treatment options depend on the size, location, and type of tumor, but may include surgical intervention, radiation therapy, or observation with periodic follow-up appointments.

Tooth ankylosis is a type of hard tissue disease that affects the teeth and jaw. It occurs when the jaw does not develop properly or when there is damage to the jawbone. This can lead to problems with chewing, speaking, and facial growth. Treatment may involve surgery, orthodontics, or other dental procedures.

Paracoccidioidomycosis is a type of primary systemic mycosis that results in a systemic fungal infection located in mucosa, lymph nodes, bone, skin or lungs and has a material basis in Paracoccidioides brasiliensis. It can also be referred to as Mucocutaneous-lymphangitic paracoccidioidomycosis or paracoccidioidal mycosis.

Blastomycosis is a type of primary systemic mycosis that results in a systemic fungal infection with a material basis in Blastomyces dermatitidis, transmitted by airborne spores, and has symptoms such as skin lesions, lung lesions, and pleural thickening. It can also be referred to as Blastomycotic infection, Chicago disease, Gilchrist's disease, Infection by Blastomyces dermatitidis, or North American blastomycosis.

Binocular vision disease, also known as strabismus, is a condition that affects the alignment of the eyes. It occurs when the two eyeballs are not properly aligned on a single point of focus, resulting in double or blurred vision. This can be caused by various factors such as genetics, brain injuries, or neurological disorders.

Binocular vision disease is characterized by the inability to see objects in three dimensions, which is known as "depth perception." People with this condition may have difficulty judging distances and might have problems with depth awareness. In some cases, binocular vision disease can also cause eye strain or headaches.

Treatment options for binocular vision disease depend on the underlying cause of the condition. In some cases, corrective lenses or eye exercises may be recommended to help realign the eyes and improve vision. Surgery may also be necessary in more severe cases to correct the alignment issues. Regular eye exams are important for early detection and treatment of this condition.

Pseudobulbar palsy is a type of brain disease that is characterized by damage to the neurons of the corticobulbar tract. It can cause symptoms such as dysarthria, dysphagia, spasticity in the tongue, gag reflex and emotional outbursts.

Vestibular neuronitis is a type of vestibulocochlear nerve disease that affects the inner ear and causes symptoms such as vertigo, nausea, and vomiting. It is usually caused by a viral infection and can occur as a complication of an upper respiratory infection. The condition has a sudden onset and may be accompanied by hearing loss. Auditory symptoms are usually absent in this condition. Vestibular neuronitis is also known as epidemic neurolabyrinthitis or vestibular neuritis.

Mixed Receptive Expressive Language Disorder (MRELD) is a type of communication disorder that affects both the understanding and use of language. It can range from mild to severe, and may involve difficulties in listening, speaking, reading, writing or using gestures. MRELD can be caused by various factors such as genetics, brain injury, hearing loss, or developmental delay. Early intervention and treatment are essential for children with MRELD to improve their communication skills and reach their full potential.

Acoustic Neurinoma (also known as Vestibular Neurilemmoma or Vestibular Schwannoma) is a benign tumor that develops from the Schwann cells surrounding the vestibular nerve. It affects the inner ear and can cause symptoms such as hearing loss, tinnitus, dizziness, and balance problems. Treatment options may include observation, surgery, or radiation therapy depending on the size and location of the tumor.

Locked-in syndrome, also known as locked-in state, is a rare neurological disorder characterized by the loss of voluntary movement in all limbs except for eye movements. It is considered a form of paralysis and is usually caused by damage to the brainstem or spinal cord. The condition may be due to various factors such as stroke, traumatic brain injury, or progressive neurological disorders like amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS). Individuals with locked-in syndrome may have difficulty speaking, swallowing, and breathing, but they can still communicate through eye movements. The condition requires specialized care from healthcare professionals and may involve physical therapy, speech therapy, and other interventions to improve quality of life.

gynecomastia is a condition that affects males where the breasts become larger and firmer than usual. This can occur due to an imbalance of hormones, such as estrogen and testosterone. Gynecomastia can be caused by a variety of factors, including puberty, medication side effects, and certain medical conditions or treatments. It is important to consult with a healthcare provider if you suspect that you have gynecomastia in order to determine the underlying cause and develop an appropriate treatment plan.

Leiomyoma refers to a type of benign neoplasm that is composed of smooth muscle cells. It is also known as leiomyomatous neoplasm or leiomyomatous tumor. The precise definition of leiomyoma is a cell type benign neoplasm that is a benign tumor of smooth muscle cells.

Hereditary hemorrhagic telangiectasia is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the presence of multiple arteriovenous malformations that lack intervening capillaries and result in direct connections between arteries and veins. It can also be referred to as Osler hemorrhagic telangiectasia syndrome, Osler-Weber-Rendu disease or Rendu-Osler-Weber disease.

Hyperprolactinemia is a condition in which the body produces too much prolactin, a hormone that stimulates milk production in women. It can also cause other symptoms such as weight gain, decreased libido, and infertility. It can be caused by various factors such as medications, tumors, or an underactive thyroid gland. Treatment may include medication to reduce prolactin levels or surgery to remove a tumor.

Ataxia telangiectasia is a rare genetic disorder that affects the cerebellum, which is part of the brain responsible for coordinating movement. It is characterized by progressive loss of motor coordination and balance, as well as other symptoms such as purple-red spider veins on the face and legs, an increased vulnerability to infections, and an increased risk of certain types of cancer. The condition is caused by mutations in the ATM gene, which is located on chromosome 11q22. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

Friedreich ataxia is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, characterized by progressive loss of coordination and balance. It is caused by a genetic mutation in the frataxin gene on chromosome 9. The condition primarily affects the cerebellum, which is responsible for coordination and balance. Symptoms often begin in childhood or adolescence and can include weakness, limb spasticity, and difficulty with fine motor skills. As the disease progresses, it can lead to scoliosis, heart problems, and diabetes. There is no cure for Friedreich ataxia, but treatments can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Myoclonic cerebellar dyssynergia is a rare neurological disorder that affects the cerebellum and brainstem. It causes muscle stiffness, tremors, and spasticity, often leading to difficulty with coordination, balance, and gait. The exact cause of the disease is not known, but it can be genetic or acquired through environmental factors such as viruses or toxins. Treatment options may include medications, physical therapy, and in some cases, surgery.

Capillary disease refers to a specific type of vascular disease that occurs in the capillaries. The exact synonym for capillary disease is "capillaritis." This condition can be located in various parts of the body, including the lungs and brain. It is important to note that capillary disease is different from other types of vascular diseases such as atherosclerosis or arteriosclerosis, which affect larger blood vessels like arteries and veins. Additionally, it has been described as being similar to interstitial lung disease (ILD), but this comparison might not be entirely accurate.

Black piedra, also known as Piedraia hortae, is a type of superficial mycosis that affects the hair shaft. This fungal infection is caused by the Piedraia hortae fungus, which forms hard black nodules on the scalp, beard, moustache and pubic hair. It is important to note that this is a superficial infection, meaning it only affects the surface of the skin and does not penetrate deeper into the tissue.

Nephronophthisis is a type of autosomal recessive kidney disease that affects the nephrons, which are the functional units of the kidneys. It is characterized by chronic tubulointerstitial nephritis that progresses to terminal renal failure during the second decade (juvenile form) or before the age of 5 years (infantile form). The disease is caused by dysfunction of ciliary proteins, which are responsible for the movement of substances in and out of the nephrons. Nephronophthisis can also be referred to as medullary cystic disease or medullary cystic kidney.

Ellis-Van Creveld syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects the development of bones and teeth. It is caused by mutations in either the EVC or EVC2 gene on chromosome 4p16.2. The condition causes short limbs, short ribs, postaxial polydactyly (an extra finger or toe on one side of the body), dysplastic nails and teeth, and congenital cardiac defects in many patients. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent.

Newborn respiratory distress syndrome (NRDS) is a type of respiratory failure that occurs in newborn infants. It is characterized by deficiency of the surfactant coating the inner surface of the lungs, failure of the lungs to expand and contract properly during breathing, resulting in collapse, and accumulation of a protein-containing film lining the alveoli and their ducts. The exact synonyms for NRDS include HMD (Hyaline membrane disease), Neonatal respiratory distress syndrome, pulmonary hyaline membrane disease, pulmonary hypoperfusion syndrome of newborn, and respiratory distress syndrome of the newborn.

Chronic gonococcal salpingitis is a specific type of chronic salpingitis caused by the bacterium Neisseria gonorrhoeae. It can cause damage to the fallopian tubes and may lead to infertility if left untreated. Symptoms include pelvic pain, abnormal menstrual bleeding, and a discharge from the vagina. It is important to seek medical attention if these symptoms are present to prevent complications and ensure proper treatment.
Telangiectasis is a condition where small blood vessels in the legs become dilated or enlarged. It is also known as telangiectasia.

Multiple epiphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by the irregular ossification centers in the hip or knee joints due to defective cartilage mineralization. This condition can cause fatigue and joint pain, which are some of its symptoms. The exact synonym for this condition is polyepiphyseal dysplasia.

respiratory syncytial virus infectious disease is a type of viral infectious disease that results in infection located in the upper respiratory tract or lower respiratory tract, has material basis in human respiratory syncytial virus, which is transmitted by droplet spread of nasal secretions from an infected person while coughing or sneezing, or contaminated fomites. The infection has symptom runny nose, fever, cough, wheezing, and respiratory distress..

Pars planitis, also known as Posterior cyclitis, is a type of chorioretinitis that affects the posterior segment of the eye. It is characterized by inflammation of the ciliary body and choroid, which can cause pain and redness in the affected eye. Pars planitis typically affects individuals between the ages of 30 and 50, and it is more common in women than men. Treatment for pars planitis usually involves corticosteroids to reduce inflammation, along with other immunosuppressive medications if needed. In some cases, a surgical procedure called a vitrectomy may be required to remove scar tissue or other damaged tissues from the eye.

Intermediate uveitis is a type of uveitis that typically affects the intermediate layer of the eye, between the choroid and the retina. It is also known as chronic cyclitis or peripheral uveoretinitis. This condition can cause inflammation, pain, and vision problems if left untreated.

Cementum is a hard tissue that forms around the teeth and helps anchor them in place. In some cases, excess cementum can accumulate on the teeth, leading to a condition known as hypercementosis or cementation hyperplasia. This can make the teeth look overgrown and may cause discomfort when eating or speaking. Treatment options for hypercementosis include removing the excess cementum through scaling and root planing, as well as using antimicrobial agents to prevent reinfection. In more severe cases, orthodontic treatment may be necessary to realign the teeth and improve their appearance. It is important to consult a dentist for proper diagnosis and treatment of this condition.

That's correct! A hernia of the ovary and fallopian tube occurs when the reproductive organs protrude through a weak spot in the abdominal wall. It can cause pain, swelling, and other symptoms, and may require surgery to repair the damage. It is important for women to be aware of their reproductive health and seek medical attention if they experience any unusual symptoms or concerns.

Cyclosporiasis is a type of coccidiosis caused by the infection of the intestine with Cyclospora cayetanensis, which can be transmitted through contaminated food and water. The symptoms associated with cyclosporiasis include watery diarrhea, anorexia, weight loss, abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting, myalgias, low-grade fever, and fatigue.

Lacrimal duct cancer is a type of cancer that affects the lacrimal system, which includes the tear production and drainage system in the eye. It is also known as malignant neoplasm of the lacrimal duct or malignant tumor of the lacrimal duct. This type of cancer can cause blockages in the tear ducts, leading to excessive tearing, swelling, and discomfort. Surgery is often used to treat this condition, and may involve removing the affected portion of the lacrimal duct or reconstructing the duct to prevent future blockages. Early detection and treatment are crucial to ensure the best possible outcome for patients with lacrimal duct cancer.

Choroid cancer is a type of uveal cancer that involves the choroid, which is a layer of blood vessels in the eye between the retina and sclera. It can also be referred to as choroidal tumor or neoplasm, which indicates the presence of an abnormal growth or mass of cells in the choroid. Malignant tumors of the choroid are also known as malignant tumor of choroid or malignant tumor of the Choroid. It is important to note that choroid cancer can be treated, but the success rate depends on various factors such as the stage and location of the cancer, as well as the patient's overall health.

Migraine without aura, also known as common migraine, is a type of migraine that is characterized by recurring episodes of headache. These headaches can be moderate to severe and can affect one or both sides of the head. They are often accompanied by other symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine without aura is the most common type of migraine and can affect people of all ages. It is important to note that while there are many treatments available for migraine, it is always recommended to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Diabetic polyneuropathy is a type of diabetic neuropathy that affects the peripheral nerves, causing pain, numbness, and weakness in the extremities. It is a common complication of diabetes mellitus and can lead to serious consequences if left untreated. Diabetic polyneuropathy is characterized by slow onset of symptoms, which may include pain, tingling, or numbness in the hands and feet. The condition can also affect the autonomic nervous system, causing issues with blood pressure regulation, digestion, and sexual function. Diabetic polyneuropathy is diagnosed through a physical examination and nerve conduction studies. Treatment options include medications to manage pain and improve nerve function, as well as lifestyle changes such as maintaining a healthy diet, exercising regularly, and monitoring blood sugar levels.

Ocular motility disease, also known as ocular motor dysfunction or disorder of eye movements, is a condition characterized by abnormal or disturbed movement of the eyes. It can affect various aspects of eye movement, including tracking, alignment, and focusing. Ocular motility diseases are often classified according to which part of the eye is affected, such as the muscles that control eye movement (cranial nerves), the visual pathways in the brain, or both.

Some common ocular motility disorders include:

1. Nystagmus: Involuntary, repetitive back-and-forth eye movements known as jerks or oscillations.
2. Strabismus: Misalignment of the eyes, which can occur in various forms such as esotropia (crossed eyes), exotropia (wandering eyes), and hypotropia (downward deviation).
3. Blepharospasm: Involuntary closing or twitching of the eyelids, often accompanied by facial spasms.
4. Ptosis: A condition where the upper eyelid droops or falls, affecting vision.
5. Ocular migraine: Short-lived visual disturbances that can cause blind spots, zigzag lines, or flashes of light in one eye.

Ocular motility diseases can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetic predisposition, environmental factors, and neurological conditions. Treatment options may vary depending on the specific disorder and its underlying cause but can include medications, botulinum toxin injections, surgery, or vision therapy. Regular eye exams are crucial for early detection and management of ocular motility diseases to prevent complications such as double vision, amblyopia (lazy eye), or permanent visual impairment.<|end_of_quote|>
hallucinogen abuse is a type of substance abuse that involves the recurring use of hallucinogenic drugs despite negative consequences.

Mucopolysaccharidosis is a type of lysosomal storage disease that affects the body's ability to break down certain types of sugar molecules. This leads to the buildup of these sugar molecules in various tissues throughout the body, including the joints, connective tissue, and organs. The accumulation of these sugar molecules can cause a variety of health problems, such as skeletal deformities, vision problems, and other developmental issues.
Mucopolysaccharidosis is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that the risk of developing the disease increases for individuals who have two copies of the affected gene (one from each parent). There are several different types of mucopolysaccharidosis, including Hurler syndrome, Hunter syndrome, and Sanfilippo syndrome. Each type of the disease is characterized by a specific set of symptoms and severity.
Treatment for mucopolysaccharidosis usually involves managing the symptoms and preventing complications. This may include enzyme replacement therapy, dietary changes, and other supportive care measures. In some cases, surgery may also be necessary to correct skeletal deformities or other physical problems caused by the disease.

Mucopolysaccharidosis II, also known as Hunter syndrome, is a type of mucopolysaccharidosis characterized by a deficiency of the lysosomal enzyme iduronate sulfatase. It is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to break down and recycle large sugar molecules called glycosaminoglycans, which are found in connective tissues throughout the body. This leads to the accumulation of mucopolysaccharides in the body, causing a range of physical and developmental symptoms.

mucopolysaccharidosis vi is a type of mucopolysaccharidosis that is characterized by a deficiency of the lysosomal enzyme N-acetylgalactosamine 4-sulfatase. It is also known as MPS VI, Maroteaux-Lamy syndrome, arylsulfatase B deficiency, and deficiency of N-acetylgalactosamine-4-sulfatase.

Mucopolysaccharidosis III, also known as MPS-III or Sanfilippo's syndrome, is a type of mucopolysaccharidosis characterized by a deficiency of the lysosomal enzyme N-sulphoglucosamine sulphohydrolase, which results in incomplete breakdown of the heparan sulfate sugar chain.

Mucopolysaccharidosis type I, also known as MPS I or Hurler syndrome, is a genetic disorder characterized by the deficiency of the lysosomal enzyme alpha-L-iduronidase. This leads to the accumulation of mucopolysaccharides in various tissues of the body, causing a range of symptoms and health problems, including vision loss, skeletal deformities, and organ dysfunction. MPS I is passed down through families and occurs due to mutations in the IDUA gene located on the long (q) arm of chromosome 2. Treatment options for MPS I include enzyme replacement therapy, which involves replacing the missing enzyme with an artificial version, and supportive care to manage symptoms and complications.

Sly syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the deficiency of the lysosomal enzyme beta-glucuronidase. This enzyme is essential for the breakdown of glycosaminoglycans, which are long chains of sugar molecules found in various connective tissues in the body, including cartilage and bone.

When there is a deficiency of beta-glucuronidase, these glycosaminoglycans can accumulate in the lysosome, which leads to the formation of large aggregates that cause damage to tissues and organs throughout the body, including the eyes, heart, liver, spleen, bones, and joints.

Sly syndrome is typically diagnosed in infancy or early childhood and can result in a range of symptoms depending on the severity of the enzyme deficiency, including skeletal abnormalities, dysostosis multiplex, cloudy urine, hepatosplenomegaly, and intellectual disability.

Treatment options for Sly syndrome include enzyme replacement therapy to supplement the missing beta-glucuronidase enzyme and help break down glycosaminoglycans. Additionally, other supportive care measures may be recommended to manage symptoms and improve quality of life.

Mucopolysaccharidosis IV, also known as MPS-IV or Morquio syndrome, is a type of mucopolysaccharidosis characterized by a deficiency in the lysosomal enzymes galactose 6-sulfate sulfatase (Type A) or beta-galactosidase (Type B), which are needed to break down the keratan sulfate sugar chain.
It is also known as Osteochondrodystrophy and chondroosteodystrophy due to the effects it has on bone and cartilage development in affected individuals.
Narrowing it down, MPS-IV specifically affects the breakdown of keratan sulfate, which is found in cartilage, cornea, and other connective tissues. This deficiency can lead to skeletal abnormalities, hearing loss, vision problems, and other health issues.
It is important for individuals with MPS-IV to receive appropriate medical care and support to manage their symptoms and improve their quality of life.

Chronic lacrimal gland enlargement (Dacryoadenitis) is a condition in which the lacrimal glands become swollen and inflamed for an extended period of time. This can lead to excessive tear production, discomfort, and potential complications such as infection. Treatment options include medications, warm compresses, and sometimes surgery.

Enterocele is a type of prolapse in female genital organs where the small intestine descends into the rectovaginal space, causing a bulge on the posterior wall of the vagina. Enterocele can be diagnosed using tests like ultrasound and MRI. Treatment options include surgery or pelvic floor exercises to strengthen the pelvic muscles.

Quadriplegia, also known as tetraplegia, is a type of neurological disorder that affects the spinal cord and results in partial or complete loss of use of all four limbs (arms and legs). It is often referred to as "quads" or "tetras." Quadriplegia can be caused by various factors, including trauma, such as a car accident or sports injury, as well as medical conditions like multiple sclerosis or spinal stenosis. The severity of quadriplegia varies from mild to severe and can impact an individual's daily life, mobility, and overall quality of life. Treatment options may include medications, physical therapy, assistive devices, and surgery, depending on the underlying cause and the specific needs of each individual.

Senile entropion, also known as involutional entropion, is a condition where the eyelids turn inward. This can cause discomfort and difficulty opening the eyes properly. It is typically seen in older adults and can be caused by age-related changes to the muscles and tissues around the eyes. Treatment options include surgery or Botox injections to correct the position of the eyelids.

Thyrotoxic crisis is a type of thyroid gland disease.
Thyrotoxic crisis has exact synonym Thyroid storm.

Prolapse of the female genital organ is a condition in which one or more pelvic structures, such as the bladder, uterus, or vagina, descend from their normal anatomical position and bulge into the vaginal canal. This can occur due to weakened pelvic floor muscles, hormonal changes, obesity, heavy lifting, or other factors. It is considered a female reproductive system disease that affects quality of life, especially when it leads to symptoms such as discomfort, pain, and urinary incontinence. Treatment options may include pelvic floor exercises, pessaries, and surgical interventions if conservative measures fail.

ancylostomiasis is a type of infection caused by the parasitic nematode Ancylostoma. It can affect various parts of the body, including the skin, eyes, and viscera. The symptoms of ancylostomiasis can include abdominal pain, diarrhea, cachexia, severe diarrhea, gastrointestinal bleeding, intestinal bleeding, anemia, severe anemia, malnutrition, skin lesions, and eye problems. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have ancylostomiasis, as it can be a serious and potentially life-threatening disease.

Guillain-Barr Syndrome (GBS) is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the peripheral nervous system. It occurs when the body's immune system mistakenly attacks part of the nerve cell sheath, causing weakness and sometimes paralysis in the limbs. GBS can be triggered by certain infections, such as those caused by bacteria like Campylobacter jejuni or viruses like Zika virus. The symptoms usually develop over a few days to weeks and can be severe enough to require hospitalization and intensive care. However, with proper treatment, most people recover within a few months.

Autistic disorder is a type of autism spectrum disorder characterized by symptoms in all three domains: communication, social, and repetitive interests and behaviors. It typically appears before the age of 3 and delays in language development are common.

text: rectal disease is a type of intestinal disease.

Achilles bursitis, also known as Achilles tendonitis or Haglund's deformity, is a condition in which the Achilles tendon becomes inflamed due to overuse or injury. This can cause pain and swelling around the heel, making it difficult to walk or stand for long periods of time. Treatment options include rest, ice, compression, elevation, physical therapy, and medication to reduce inflammation and pain. In severe cases, surgery may be necessary to repair the damaged tendon.

huntington s disease is a type of neurodegenerative disease that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and is characterized by unwanted choreatic movements, behavioral and psychiatric disturbances and dementia. The disease results from the expansion of CAG triplet repeats (glutamine) which leads to neuron degeneration affecting muscle coordination, cognitive abilities.

That's correct! Chorea is a type of movement disorder that is characterized by brief, semi-directed, irregular movements that do not repeat in a specific pattern. It often affects the face and limbs and can be caused by various conditions such as Huntington's disease or syphilis. Hereditary chorea specifically refers to the inheritance of the condition from one's parents. Is there anything else I can help you with?

Cardiovascular system disease refers to a condition that affects the heart, blood vessels, or other components of the circulatory system. These diseases can include conditions such as heart attacks, stroke, high blood pressure, and various types of cardiovascular disorders. The cardiovascular system is responsible for delivering oxygen and nutrients to the body's cells and tissues, as well as removing waste products from them. Therefore, any disease or disorder that affects this system can have serious consequences for overall health and wellbeing.

What is the definition of hypochondriasis?
Hypochondriasis is a type of somatoform disorder that involves an excessive preoccupation or worry about having a serious illness.

Miller Fisher Syndrome (MFS) is a specific type of Guillain-Barre syndrome (GBS) that affects the nerve cells in the body, leading to muscle weakness and paralysis. It is characterized by a descending pattern of symptoms, which means that the symptoms typically start at the top of the body and progress downwards.

MFS often affects the eye muscles first, causing ophthalmoplegia (difficulty moving the eyes). This is followed by ataxia (problems with balance and coordination) and areflexia (loss of reflexes), which together make up the "triad" of symptoms associated with MFS.

It's important to note that while MFS can be a serious condition, most people recover with treatment. However, in some cases, it can lead to long-term complications such as muscle weakness and difficulty swallowing. If you suspect you or someone you know may have MFS, it's crucial to seek medical attention immediately.

That is correct. Neurodegenerative diseases are a class of disorders characterized by the progressive decline in function and structure of neurons in the central nervous system. They can affect various parts of the brain, including motor, sensory, and cognitive functions, leading to symptoms such as loss of memory, difficulty speaking or moving, and changes in personality or mood. Examples of neurodegenerative diseases include Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, and Huntington's disease. It is important to note that while these conditions may have similar symptoms, they are distinct diseases with different causes and treatments.

Sjogren's syndrome is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the exocrine glands, which are responsible for producing saliva and tears. It is also known as Sicca syndrome or xerodermosteosis. This condition occurs when the immune system attacks and destroys these glands, leading to dryness in the mouth, eyes, nose, and throat.
Keratoconjunctivitis sicca, also known as KCS, is a type of dry eye syndrome.

Submandibular gland disease refers to any condition that affects the submandibular gland, which is a small salivary gland located below the jawbone on each side of the face. It is one type of salivary gland disease.

Benign lymphoepithelial lesion of the salivary gland, also known as Godwin tumor, is a type of salivary gland disease characterized by the presence of abnormal lymphoid tissue in the mucous membranes of the salivary glands. It is usually benign and slow-growing, but can become cancerous if left untreated. Symptoms may include swelling or enlargement of the affected salivary gland, difficulty swallowing, and pain or discomfort in the area. Treatment options for Godwin tumors typically involve surgical removal of the affected tissue, although radiation therapy or other treatments may also be used in some cases.

Mikulicz disease is a type of autoimmune disorder that affects the glands in the head and neck area. It is characterized by chronic enlargement of these glands, lumps on the face and neck, dry eyes, dry mouth, and intermittent fever. The disease can be associated with other underlying conditions such as hematologic malignancy, tuberculosis infection, or syphilis infection. It is also sometimes referred to by the exact synonyms IgG4-related dacryoadenitis and sialadenitis, or simply Mikulicz's disease.

text: necrotizing sialometaplasia is a type of salivary gland disease.

Mucocele of the salivary gland, also known as a mucous retention cyst or ranula, is a benign, fluid-filled sac that forms within the salivary gland. It is caused by blockage of saliva flow, either due to inflammation or obstruction by debris, bacteria, or other foreign substances. Symptoms may include swelling on one side of the face, difficulty opening the mouth, and pain when biting or chewing. Treatment options for mucocele of salivary gland include observation, surgical excision, or sclerotherapy, depending on the size, location, and symptoms of the cyst.

Sialolithiasis is a medical condition in which a salivary gland or duct becomes blocked by a stone, also known as a salivary gland stone. This blockage can cause pain and difficulty swallowing. Sialolithiasis affects the salivary glands located in the head and neck, and it is more common in people over the age of 40. The condition requires medical treatment to remove the stones and restore normal function to the affected gland or duct.

Thromboangiitis obliterans is a type of peripheral vascular disease, which is characterized by the narrowing or blocking of blood vessels in the extremities (arms and legs). It can lead to symptoms such as pain, numbness, and gangrene. Another name for this condition is Buerger's disease, and it is sometimes referred to as presenile gangrene.

Plasmodium ovale malaria is a type of malaria caused by the parasite Plasmodium ovale. It is characterized by tertian chills and febrile paroxysms, which end spontaneously. This form of malaria is generally considered to be relatively mild compared to other forms of the disease.

Hypodermyiasis is a type of myiasis that involves the parasitic infestation of warble flies, specifically Hypoderma species, on cattle and deer. The larvae feed in subdermal cavities, causing cutaneous swellings and potentially producing discharges and being painful.

A myiasis is a type of infestation caused by the feeding habits of certain bird species, which can lead to damage or infection in humans or animals. Screw worm infectious disease is a specific form of myiasis that is caused by Cochliomyia hominivorax or Chrysomya bezziana larvae, which feed on the living tissues of warm-blooded animals. In Cochliomyia infestation, larvae migrate from the subdermis to other tissues in the body, causing extreme damage in the process. Chrysomya bezziana larvae feed and can cause permanent tissue damage.

endocardial fibroelastosis is a type of endocardium disease.
endocardial fibroelastosis has the definition An inmost lining of heart chambers thickening due to increase supporting connective tissue and elastic fibers.
endocardial fibroelastosis has exact synonym Elastomyofibrosis.
endocardial fibroelastosis has exact match MESH:D004695.

labia minora carcinoma is a type of cancer that affects the labia minora, which are the inner lips of the female genital area. It is also known as vulva carcinoma and can be further subclassified into different types based on the specific location and characteristics of the tumor. Labia minora carcinoma can occur at any age but is more common in postmenopausal women. The symptoms of labia minora carcinoma may include abnormal bleeding, discharge, or itching, and a lump or swelling in the affected area. If detected early, labia minora carcinoma can be treated with surgery, radiation therapy, or chemotherapy, but it is essential to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Dilated cardiomyopathy is a type of intrinsic cardiomyopathy characterized by an enlarged heart and damage to the myocardium, causing it to pump blood inefficiently. The exact synonym for this condition is primary dilated cardiomyopathy. It is related to congestive cardiomyopathy, familial dilated cardiomyopathy, idiopathic dilation cardiomyopathy, and dilated cardiomyopathy of unknown cause.

Endomyocardial fibrosis is a type of restrictive cardiomyopathy, characterized by the excessive deposition of extracellular matrix in the myocardium. This can lead to fibrotic scarring and thickening of the heart muscle, resulting in reduced contractility and decreased blood flow to the heart.

Synonyms for endomyocardial fibrosis include African endomyocardial fibrosis, Becker's disease, Endomyocardial sclerosis, and obscure African cardiomyopathy. It is important to note that these terms are often used interchangeably, although some sources may use specific terms based on the geographic origin or clinical presentation of the condition.

It is also worth noting that endomyocardial fibrosis can be caused by a variety of factors, including viral infections, autoimmune diseases, and drug toxicity. Treatment options may vary depending on the underlying cause and severity of the condition, but may include medications, surgery, or other interventions as needed.

Alcoholic cardiomyopathy is a type of extrinsic cardiomyopathy that occurs due to long-term alcohol consumption. It is characterized by the weakening and enlargement of the heart muscle, which can lead to difficulties in pumping blood throughout the body. The condition has been associated with excessive alcohol intake over an extended period, leading to damage to the heart muscle and eventually causing it to become dilated.

Alcoholic cardiomyopathy is considered a type of Alcohol-induced cardiomyopathy or Dilated Cardiomyopathy secondary to alcohol, which are more precise terms that accurately describe the condition caused by excessive alcohol consumption. The disease driver for alcoholic cardiomyopathy is primarily alcohol, and it is considered a preventable form of heart disease. With proper treatment and lifestyle modifications, individuals who suffer from alcoholic cardiomyopathy can improve their condition and reduce the risk of developing more severe complications.

vulva carcinoma is a type of vulvar cancer.
vulva carcinoma is a type of carcinoma.
vulva carcinoma is a type of cancer that derives from epithelial cells in the vulva region.
vulva carcinoma has definition A vulvar cancer that has_material_basis_in abnormally proliferating cells derives_from epithelial cells..
vulva carcinoma has exact synonym Vulvar carcinoma.
vulva carcinoma has related synonym Carcinoma of the vulva.

Acrocephalosyndactylia, also known as Apert syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the premature fusion of certain cranial bones and fingers or toes. It occurs when there are mutations in one of several genes involved in regulating growth and development. Symptoms can include an abnormal head shape (mandibulofacial dysostosis), polydactyly (more than five fingers on the hands or more than ten toes on the feet), and craniosynostosis (premature fusion of skull bones). Acrocephalosyndactylia can also affect other body parts, such as the limbs, neck, and genitals. In some cases, it may cause developmental delays or intellectual disability. Treatment typically involves surgery to correct deformities and improve function.

Poland's syndrome is a rare congenital disorder that affects the development of muscles, bones, and skin on one side of the body. It is characterized by the absence or underdevelopment of muscles, as well as abnormalities in the bone structure and skin. The condition can cause various problems, including deformities of the chest, shoulder, arm, and hand, and can also affect the development of the affected limb. In some cases, Poland's syndrome may be associated with other congenital anomalies, such as heart defects or cleft lip and palate. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you or someone you know may have this condition.

Yes, subleukemic leukemia is a type of leukemia that is characterized by the presence of abnormal white blood cells in peripheral blood, but with a normal total number of white blood cells. It is also known as leukemia cutis.

Central nervous system leukemia, also known as CNS leukemia or Leukemia of the CNS, is a type of hematologic cancer that occurs in the central nervous system. It is characterized by the abnormal proliferation and accumulation of immature white blood cells in the brain and spinal cord.
CNS leukemia can cause various symptoms such as headaches, nausea, vomiting, seizures, balance and coordination problems, memory loss, and personality changes. It is often diagnosed through a combination of imaging tests, cerebrospinal fluid analysis, and bone marrow biopsy.
Treatment for CNS leukemia typically involves a multi-disciplinary approach that includes chemotherapy, radiation therapy, stem cell transplantation, and targeted therapy. The prognosis of CNS leukemia depends on various factors such as the age of the patient, the extent of the disease, and the type of leukemia cells present. With early diagnosis and appropriate treatment, patients with CNS leukemia can have a better chance of survival.

Hereditary spherocytosis is a type of congenital hemolytic anemia, where red blood cells have a sphere shape instead of the normal biconcave disk shape. It is also known as Congenital spherocytic hemolytic anemia, Minkowski Chauffard syndrome, and Spherocytic anemia.

intrapelvic lymph node leukemic reticuloendotheliosis is a type of cancer that affects the intrapelvic lymph nodes. It is also known as Leukemic reticuloendotheliosis involving intrapelvic lymph nodes or Leukemic reticuloendotheliosis of intrapelvic lymph nodes.

Plasmodium vivax malaria is a type of malaria that is caused by the protozoan parasite Plasmodium vivax. The condition causes periodic fever, with each paroxysm lasting approximately 12 hours and occurring every 48 hours. It is one of the most common forms of human malaria and is predominantly found in Southeast Asia and South America. In addition to its health effects on humans, Plasmodium vivax can also be transmitted to animals such as horses and dogs.

Neoplasm of the vagus nerve is a type of tumor that develops from the cells of the vagus nerve. These tumors can be benign or malignant, and they can cause various symptoms depending on their location and size. They are also known as Vagus Nerve Tumors. If you have been diagnosed with a neoplasm of the vagus nerve, it is important to seek medical treatment from a qualified healthcare professional.

Agranulocytosis is a type of leukopenia, which means there are low levels of white blood cells in the blood. In this case, it specifically refers to a lack of granulocytes, which are a type of white blood cell that help fight infections. It's defined as a condition where the concentration of granulocytes drops below 200 cells per microliter (mm) of blood. It's also known as granulocytopenic disorder or granulopenia, and it can be caused by various factors such as infections, certain medications, or genetic conditions. If left untreated, agranulocytosis can increase the risk of infections and other complications, so it's important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have this condition.

Conduct disorder is a type of developmental disorder that typically emerges in childhood and adolescence. It is characterized by a pattern of behavior that violates the rights of others or social norms, and often includes aggressive behavior towards people or animals, destruction of property, and deceitfulness or lying. It is estimated that about 5% to 8% of children and adolescents have conduct disorder. In some cases, it may be associated with other conditions such as attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) or mood disorders like bipolar disorder. If left untreated, conduct disorder can lead to more serious problems in adulthood, including criminal behavior and difficulties in relationships. Treatment typically involves a combination of therapy, medication, and behavioral interventions.

acute dacryocystitis is a type of dacryocystitis.
dacryocystitis - acute, dacryocystitis - chronic are synonyms for acute dacryocystitis.

Stenosis, carotid artery and Carotid artery stenosis are alternative names for the same condition.

Subclavian steal syndrome is a condition where there is narrowing or blockage of the subclavian artery, which can lead to reduced blood flow and potential complications. It can also cause symptoms such as pain in the shoulder, neck, and arm, and difficulty moving the arms. Treatment options for this condition may include medications to improve blood flow, angioplasty or stenting procedures to widen the artery, or surgical options like bypass grafts. It is essential to consult a healthcare professional if you suspect that you have subclavian steal syndrome.

Vertebrobasilar insufficiency (VBI) is a type of transient cerebral ischemia. It occurs when the vertebral and basilar arteries that supply blood to the brain are not able to provide sufficient blood flow, leading to hypoxia or reduced oxygenation of the brain. This can result in symptoms such as dizziness, lightheadedness, syncope, visual disturbances, and stroke-like symptoms. VBI is often referred to by different names, including Vertebrobasilar insufficiency, Vertebrobasilar arterial insufficiency, and Vertebrobasilar artery syndrome. It can also be matched with the MESH term D014715 for reference.

intra abdominal lymph node mast cell malignancy is a type of lymph node cancer that occurs when mast cells in the intra-abdominal lymph nodes become cancerous.
intra abdominal lymph node mast cell malignancy is a type of mast cell neoplasm that develops from mast cells in the intra-abdominal lymph nodes.
intra abdominal lymph node mast cell malignancy is a type of cancer that starts in the mast cells found in the intra-abdominal lymph nodes.
intra abdominal lymph node mast cell malignancy has exact synonym Mast cell cancer of intra-abdominal lymph nodes.
intra abdominal lymph node mast cell malignancy has exact synonym malignant mast cells in the intra-abdominal lymph nodes.

Shipyard eye, also known as epidemic keratoconjunctivitis (EKC), is a type of keratoconjunctivitis that affects individuals working in shipyards. It is caused by the chronic exposure to wood dust and other irritants found in such work environments. The condition can cause symptoms like redness, itching, and discomfort in the eyes, as well as vision impairment if left untreated. To prevent or manage shipyard eye, individuals working in these environments should wear proper protective gear, including safety glasses or contact lenses, and follow established hygiene practices to reduce exposure to irritants.

Retinopathy of prematurity is a condition that affects the retina, specifically in premature infants. It is also known as Retrolental fibroplasia and premature retinopathy. These terms all refer to the same disease.

lobomycosis is a type of dermatomycosis that results in an infection located in the skin or subcutaneous tissue, and has a material basis in Lacazia loboi. It can cause symptoms such as crusty plaques, tumors, and nodular lesions. Another name for this condition is cutaneous lobomycosis, and it can be related to cutaneous blastomycosis.
Transient global amnesia is a type of amnestic disorder that is characterized by temporary but almost total disruption of short-term memory, with problems accessing older memories.

Relapsing fever is a primary bacterial infectious disease that results from infection with the bacteria Borrelia. It has a material basis in Borrelia and can be transmitted by tick or body louse.

Relapsing fever is a type of illness that can be transmitted by the bites of certain ticks.
Relapsing fever is a type of illness that can also be spread through contact with an infected individual.
